{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 1. Purpose of this Document \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b This document aims to agree on a broad, international strategy for the implementation of open scholarship that meets the needs of different national and regional communities but works globally.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Scholarly research can be idealised as an inspirational process for advancing our collective knowledge to the benefit of all humankind. However, current research practices often struggle with a range of tensions, in part due to the fact that this collective (or "commons") ideal conflicts with the competitive system in which most scholars work, and in part because much of the infrastructure of the scholarly world is becoming largely digital. What is broadly termed as {\i Open Scholarship} is an attempt to realign modern research practices with this ideal. We do not propose a definition of Open Scholarship, but recognise that it is a holistic term that encompasses many disciplines, practices, and principles, sometimes also referred to as Open Science or Open Research. We choose the term Open Scholarship to be more inclusive of these other terms. When we refer to science in this document, we do so historically and use it as shorthand for more general scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The purpose of this document is to provide a concise analysis of where the global Open Scholarship movement currently stands: what the common threads and strengths are, where the greatest opportunities and challenges lie, and how we can more effectively work together as a global community to recognise and address the top strategic priorities. This document was inspired by the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.oerstrategy.org/home/read-the-doc/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Foundations for OER Strategy Development
}}}
 and work in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.force11.org/group/scholarly-commons-working-group"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
FORCE11 Scholarly Commons Working Group
}}}
, and developed by an open contribution working group.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Our hope is that this document will serve as a foundational resource for continuing discussions and initiatives about implementing effective strategies to help streamline the integration of Open Scholarship practices into a modern, digital research culture. Through this, we hope to extend the reach and impact of Open Scholarship into a global context, making sure that it is truly {\i open for all}. We also hope that this document will evolve as the conversations around Open Scholarship progress, and help to provide useful insight for both global co-ordination and local action. We believe this is a step forward in making Open Scholarship the norm.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ultimately, we expect the impact of widespread adoption of Open Scholarship to be diverse. We expect novel research practices to accelerate the pace of innovation, and therefore stimulate critical industries around the world. We could also expect to see an increase in public trust of science and scholarship, as transparency becomes more normative. As such, we expect interest in Open Scholarship to increase at multiple levels, due to its inherent influence on society and global economics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 2. Strategy \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 "{\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strategy"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Strategy
}}}
 generally involves setting goals, determining actions to achieve the goals, and mobilizing resources to execute the actions. A strategy describes how the ends (goals) will be achieved by the means (resources).}"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 Due to the length of this strategy, please note that we have also compiled a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/Open-Scholarship-Strategy/site/blob/master/immediate-action-plan.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\b IMMEDIATE ACTION PLAN}
}}}
 comprising the most essential immediate strategic action points.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In order to overcome the challenges and achieve our priorities, we need to build on our strengths. We have identified three main temporal components (short-, mid-, and long-term) of our overall strategy to be used as direct suggestions for action on the individual, group, institutional or national (or higher) level. We notice that this hierarchy does not fully represent the connectivity of different levels of the academic system (e.g., at the discipline level). There is clearly a need for different fields to discuss what is culturally appropriate for themselves; however, this strategy can provide a foundation for guiding those discussions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 With this, one of the principle goals for this strategy is to create communities that reciprocally support each other through learning and training (e.g., via the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://eliademy.com/opensciencemooc"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science MOOC
}}}
). These communities will have the best insight into real life barriers and how to overcome them, and will be able to identify new realities at the different hierarchical levels, which can then be incorporated into decision making processes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We note that, due to the diversity of actors and stakeholders and their views and practices, this strategy is not a consensus document. How the different aspects are prioritised is a matter of debate based on varying perspectives. Its effectiveness will be realised when individuals and communities can implement different parts of it as cultural norms develop and shift towards a more open state.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many view the progress of Open Scholarship in the last 2-3 decades as painfully insubstantive, a factor that might reflect a general lack of strategic thinking and implementation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We also note that this strategy can only be based on information which we as a collective have, and it remains highly likely that there are many initiatives, policies, and programs that we have inadvertently missed. As such, it is probable that there are strategies that we have missed or not even considered. Nonetheless, we have attempted to justify our strategy where possible using evidence and reasoning, the discussion of which can be found below the strategy in Section 5.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 2.1 Short-term strategy (>2 years) \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Individual Level\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.1147024"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Kramer, Bianca, & Bosman, Jeroen (2018, January). Rainbow of open science practices. Zenodo
}}}
. (CC BY) Note that the strategy below is divided into the 6 Major categories (search, analysis, writing, publication, outreach, and assessment) where relevant.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Search\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Search for existing data you can reuse instead of creating your own data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider using and supporting more open search engines, such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openknowledgemaps.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Knowledge Maps
}}}
, instead of proprietary services.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Also make sure that all of your research outputs are easily discoverable, published either in journals, websites, or other repositories, and with appropriate identifiers and metadata.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use RSS readers such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://feedly.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Feedly
}}}
 to easily aggregate news and research updates from a number of sources.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Analysis\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt a broad-scale approach to the variety of open scholarly research and education practices. See the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.fosteropenscience.eu/resources"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
FOSTER Open Science taxonomy
}}}
 for guidance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt the use of open source and/or free software for the conduct of research and analysis so that the computational processing can be audited by the community, and so that the tools used are available to everyone to increase productivity and collaboration.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For the distinction between open, free, gratis and libre, see. e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://opensource.com/article/17/11/open-source-or-free-software"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
OpenSource.com
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Establish and foster practices of re-use and remix to help create a thriving open scholarship culture, based around collaboration and sharing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where needed, also consider pre-registering studies, sharing protocols, and using lab notebooks to openly document research.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Writing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Answer relevant questions and join in discussions on public websites, e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ask-open-science.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Ask Open Science
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://stackoverflow.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Stack Overflow
}}}
, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.reddit.com/r/Open_Science/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science subreddit
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Twitter
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make individual contributions to openness that are visible in public (e.g., on a CV, open platform, or personal website/blog). Use these as the basis to develop best practice stories around role models.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Become familiar with openly collaborative writing tools such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.overleaf.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Overleaf
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Google Docs
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Also consider 'executable writing formats' using platforms such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://stenci.la/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Stencila
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Publication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Commit to a variety of personal open scholarly practices, such as sharing research data and materials in free, openly-licensed formats so that methods and results can be freely examined and built upon by the wider community.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Also consider sharing your work more rapidly via use of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://osf.io/preprints/bitss/796tu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
preprints
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make sure that all supporting code, data, and other relevant information are available alongside any papers published.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Commit to sharing presentations and posters, as well as any recordings, online via platforms such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://zenodo.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Zenodo
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Most importantly, begin with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cyber.harvard.edu/hoap/How_to_make_your_own_work_open_access"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
making your own work available open access
}}}
, which can almost always be done in some way at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://figshare.com/collections/How_to_make_your_work_100_Open_Access_for_free_and_legally_multi-lingual_/3943972"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
no cost
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider only publishing in APC-free Open Access journals, or those which or operated by non-profits or learned societies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to sign copyright transfer agreements (CTAs), unless you are allowed to retain copyright of your work under a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://creativecommons.org/licenses"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Creative Commons
}}}
 license of your own choosing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If needed, use the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sparcopen.org/our-work/author-rights/brochure-html/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
SPARC author addendum
}}}
 to legally retain the rights to your work during publicaton.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Outreach\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Advocate for funding organisations, governments, research institutions, journals, conferences, and professional societies to adopt policies and mandates related to Open Scholarship practices beyond Open Access (OA) and data sharing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For example, on open peer review, use of persistent identifiers (PIDs), open research evaluation, and preprints.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Further to that, advocate for open education with corresponding practices in order to help spread approaches to open among peers and the next generation of scientists.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Work with, and collaborate with, researchers who practice various aspects of Open Scholarship, ranging from developing Open Source software and tools to posting preprints and citizen science, and sharing experiences made with approaches to open education.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For education, sign the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.capetowndeclaration.org/sign-the-declaration"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Cape Town Open Education Declaration
}}}
 to commit to the pursuit of the Declaration's three strategies as a part of one's teaching, learning and/or work life.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage the wider adoption of an open mindset that emphasises the importance of the research process over the outcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Establish support structures (e.g., open workshops, openLabs, walk-in labs and support structures, makerspaces in the wider sense) that help to guide other individuals along the path towards Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This can include questions of how to publish, teach, learn and do research in the open, and what tools are available to use for these (see Figures 1 and 2, and {\i Group Level} section).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Form better relationships with other stakeholders involved in Open Scholarship developments (e.g., librarians, policymakers, publishers and other service providers, Open Access advocates, and those actively teaching, plus ICT and other support positions for science & education).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make sure to heed the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.capetowndeclaration.org/cpt10/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Ten Directions to Move Open Education Forward
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider supporting community initiatives such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://opensciencemooc.eu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science MOOC
}}}
 for more widespread training in open scientific practices.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Assessment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Leave {\b constructive} comments/annotations on preprints/code etc. with open tools such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://web.hypothes.is/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
hypothes.is
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab React positively to requests for open peer review, and requests from non-profits and learned societies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Also consider refusing to perform peer review (and editorial work) for free to commercial publishers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Request that all relevant materials (data, software, etc.) be made open and be properly cited in your reviewing, as per the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://opennessinitiative.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Peer Reviewers' Openness Initiative
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sign the San Francisco Declaration on Research Assessment {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sfdora.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
(DORA)
}}}
 as a commitment to improving how research is assessed. Make sure to adhere to the principles too in practice.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.leidenmanifesto.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Leiden Manifesto
}}}
 for research metrics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Do not judge work based on its impact factor or venue of publication. Consider establishing an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://impactstory.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ImpactStory profile
}}}
 to document your research impact more.\sa180\par}
