{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Group Level (e.g., labs, departments)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Many of those at the individual level will still be relevant here too, and are duplicated in part here to reflect this.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Search\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Search for existing data from other labs and individuals you can reuse instead of creating your own duplicate data.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider using and supporting more open search engines, such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openknowledgemaps.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Knowledge Maps
}}}
, instead of proprietary services.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use RSS readers such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://feedly.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Feedly
}}}
 to easily aggregate news and research updates from a number of sources.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Analysis\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt best practices for Open Scholarship, including shared data as a research output, addressing publication bias, and "questionable research practices" with bias-reducing workflows.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Highlight best practice showcases in order to demonstrate what is actually possible with Open Scholarship, and what the wider advantages can be.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt a broad-scale approach to the variety of open scholarly research practices. See the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.fosteropenscience.eu/resources"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
FOSTER Open Science taxonomy
}}}
 for a starting point, and further expand this to include e.g. Social Sciences and the Humanities as well as Education and Scholarly Communication practices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Most importantly, begin with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cyber.harvard.edu/hoap/How_to_make_your_own_work_open_access"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
making your own work available open access
}}}
, which can almost always be done in some way at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://figshare.com/collections/How_to_make_your_work_100_Open_Access_for_free_and_legally_multi-lingual_/3943972"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
no cost
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt the use of open source and/or free software for the conduct of research and analysis so that the computational processing can be audited by the community, and so that the tools used are available to everyone to increase productivity and collaboration.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where needed, also consider pre-registering studies, sharing protocols, and using lab notebooks to openly document research.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Writing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Answer relevant questions and join in discussions on public websites, e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ask-open-science.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Ask Open Science
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://stackoverflow.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Stack Overflow
}}}
, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.reddit.com/r/Open_Science/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science subrredit
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Twitter
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider having group/lab profiles where needed on these platforms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Commit to using openly collaborative writing tools such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.overleaf.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Overleaf
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Google Docs
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Publication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers who have restrictive preprint, Open Access, and copyright policies, or are otherwise antagonstic to progressive open scholarship practices and policies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Commit to sharing {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://asapbio.org/preprint-info"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
preprints
}}}
 for the open and rapid dissemination of your work.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make sure that all supporting code, data, and other relevant information are available alongside any papers published.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Outreach\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Locate Open Scholarship hotspots (i.e., venues or groups for regular exchange and discussion about community building) and find a way to link them together to help community cohesion and expansion.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If a local Open Scholarship hotspot does not yet exist, establish it (e.g., using the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.meetup.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Meetup
}}}
 platform).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use these national/international/regional communities to support lower-level learning and knowledge sharing of Open Scholarship practices, especially in varying cultural settings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start discussions towards an implicit or explicit (shared) open science pledge or code of conduct for your department, lab, or research group. This can be based on existing ones, such as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.contributor-covenant.org/de/version/1/4/code-of-conduct"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Contributor Covenant
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Establish rights experts who might help with questions regarding copyright issues and the effective use of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://creativecommons.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Creative Commons
}}}
 licenses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Advocate to decision makers at scholarly journals, publishers, funders, and higher education and research institutions to recognize and reward a variety of Open Scholarship activities, particularly regarding research evaluation and open education policies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Initiate debates on meaningful standards and practices at a disciplinary level for publishing data (e.g., the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.go-fair.org/fair-principles/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
FAIR principles
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Improve engagement between faculty advisory boards, researchers, students and librarians regarding Open Scholarship practices (see Fig. 1 and 2) and principles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1002/leap.1228"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Hartley et al. 2019
}}}
's notion of expert user communities that might also be expanded to not only encompass OA publishing, but also other Open Science and Scholarship tools, services and corresponding communities in the variety of areas of Open Scholarship.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Assessment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Engage communication departments and research assessment officials. Organize sessions to tell them about open science and scholarship, and be sensitive to the fact that it may imply they change their entire view of what is important in science and what their role could be.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Start discussions with University Ranking Providers (e.g., QS, Times Higher Education) to include an openness element to their indicators.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Institute Level (including research and funding bodies, and professional societies)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Sharing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Explore substituting proprietary software with open source alternatives.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Require researchers to work with open standards and file formats (either exclusively or in addition to proprietary standards and file formats).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Publication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Map and coordinate when current subscription and big deal licenses will run out across research institutes, and let it happen. Where cancellations or terminations occur, ensure that there is adequate post-subscription access and support using existing sustainable and legal mechanisms (e.g., Inter-Library Loan).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make sure that there is sufficient co-ordination between libraries and relevant others beforehand, so that libraries can continue to provide outstanding services without interruption.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Explore routes for reinvesting money saved for library budgets.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Purchase back any legacy documents and incorporate them into the scholarly body of work. Also improve the open sharing and archiving of legacy articles on which copyright has expired.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Help to inform researchers more about the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.authorsalliance.org/resources/termination-of-transfer/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Author Alliance termination of transfer
}}}
 tool to help them retain their rights as authors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research funders can define the limits of what is an acceptable standard of publication. They therefore have the power to mandate publication in journals with a cap on APCs and BPCs, or in OA-only venues (with specific licenses), or in those with short or zero-length embargoes on self-archiving (e.g., Emerald, The Royal Society).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.rluk.ac.uk/about-us/blog/the-costs-of-double-dipping/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
double dip
}}}
 on payments.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Demand transparency and data in cases where there is a suspicion that this is occurring (for an overview, see e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theguardian.com/science/2017/jun/27/profitable-business-scientific-publishing-bad-for-science"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Buranyi, 2017
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers in which there is no transparency around pricing for either subscriptions or Open Access. This includes with publishers who insist on using non-disclosure agreements as part of licensing contract terms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Engage publishers on being more transparent about the financial aspects of their publishing workflows, similar to those such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ubiquitypress.com/site/publish/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Ubiquity Press
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Refuse to engage with publishers who have restrictive preprint, Open Access, or copyright policies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Insist that publishers make all bibliographic records, usage metrics, and citation data freely available and accessible in both a human- and machine-readable format.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Develop rights retention policies for scholarly research at research institutes that currently lack them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adopt the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://docs.casrai.org/CRediT"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
CASRAI CRediT
}}}
 (Contributor Rules Taxonomy) guidelines to help identify paper author contributions more clearly, and additionally identify the contributions of authors of other products (data, software, etc.) as clearly as possible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage further adoption by publishers of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://i4oc.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Initiative for Open Citations
}}}
 (I4OC) in conjunction with the wider uptake of open standards.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For research institutes that currently lack them, either launch and maintain an Open Access repository or find an existing resource to use, and adopt an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cyber.harvard.edu/hoap/Good_practices_for_university_open-access_policies"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Access policy
}}}
. Make these easily discoverable and accessible on the institutional website, and any relevant indexing services.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Examples of Open Access policies can be found e.g. via the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://roarmap.eprints.org/cgi/search/advanced"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ROARMAP
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Examples of Open Education / OER policies are listed in e.g. the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wiki.creativecommons.org/wiki/OER_Policy_Registry"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Creative Commons OER policy registry
}}}
, or the European Union's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.2760/283135"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Policy approaches to Open Education, 2017
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Outreach\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research libraries should collect information about how the sector as a whole interacts with the research literature. Such information could be used to help with publisher negotiations, break up big deal contracts, and cancel subscriptions by providing evidence into the cross-sectorial value of services, and includes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Which venues researchers are publishing in;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Who is doing the editorial and peer review work;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab How much is being spent on serial subscriptions;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab How much is being spent on Article Processing Charges (APCs) and Book Processing Charges (BPCs) for Open Access; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Which articles are being downloaded and cited.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Promote and compensate time and effort spent on training and advocacy for the various aspects of Open Scholarship, including Open Source, Open Access, and Open Education.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Enable and foster local support structures such as openlabs and open publication and research learning, guidance and advice offers.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Assessment\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Engage with research communities to develop and advertise quantifiable incentives for sharing preprints, open data, reproducible analyses, and OA in hiring, promotion, and tenure decisions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Define new ways of describing these wider contributions to scientific communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage and adopt the principles for fairer research assessment outlined in DORA.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Make sure that those in charge of research assessment, including hiring, tenure, and grant-awarding committees adhere to these.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Explore the Dutch paradigm of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openworking.wordpress.com/2018/06/24/changing-the-academic-reward-system-the-umc-utrecht-perspective/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
researchers' portfolios
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 National Level (or higher)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Search\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Implement currently available sort, filter and search/discovery technology across scholarship outputs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Enable unrestricted text and data mining over this content.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Writing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mandate {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://orcid.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ORCID
}}}
 for researchers across all research outputs to help assist in the persistent identification of authors across the entire research literature, and easier research discoverability.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Publication\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Build on faculty and funder support for Open Access and related quality assurance initiatives (e.g., peer review) that are decoupled from journals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Agree on, and develop, a governance structure for a world-wide scholarly infrastructure (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.w3.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
W3C
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create scholarly standards to implement an alternative non-profit and community-owned scholarly publishing platform/environment (using the funds freed from subscriptions, building on existing repositories/environments and infrastructure).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A reduction of article-processing charges (APCs) in hybrid titles to match the market average for OA-only journals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab NOTE that with the new funding stream of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ec.europa.eu/info/designing-next-research-and-innovation-framework-programme/what-shapes-next-framework-programme_en"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
HorizonEurope
}}}
, publications to hybrid journals are not eligible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A reduction of article-processing charges (APCs) and book-processing charges (BPCs) in hybrid titles to match the market average for OA-only journals and presses.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The scholarly publishing market might require a detailed government-level investigation in order to stabilise this.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where subscriptions have not yet expired, mandate offsetting agreements for hybrid journal titles in order to reduce double-dipping.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where offsetting deals are in place, these can be streamlined and standardised across sectors to reduce administrative burden.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For scholarly publishers to engage with the new {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://ukscl.ac.uk/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
UK Scholarly Communications License
}}}
 that enables authors to retain more of their rights.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This would reduce the time spent on embargo processing, the cost spent on hybrid APCs and BPCs, and for researchers in the UK, help them to comply with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ukri.org/funding/information-for-award-holders/open-access/open-access-policy/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
UKRI Open Access policy
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For those outside of the UK to consider extending the UK SCL (or relevant variations of it) towards other regional funding and licensing strategies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sector-wide adoption of no-questions-asked fee waiver policies for researchers from lower- to middle-income countries, or those with a demonstrable financial need.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://nrs.harvard.edu/urn-3:HUL.InstRepos:27803834"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
transform
}}}
 (or flip) the majority of scholarly journals from subscription to Open Access publishing in accordance with community-specific publication preferences.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs24 Outreach\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create new or support/contact existing international library consortia/collaborations (e.g., the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://icolc.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
International Coalition of Library Consortia
}}}
) to co-operate on infrastructure developments (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://libereurope.eu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
LIBER
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.eifl.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
EIFL
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.arl.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ARL
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sparcopen.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
SPARC
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sign on to the Global Sustainability Coalition for Open Science Services {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://scoss.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
(SCOSS)
}}}
, and investigate coalitions with the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.orfg.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Research Funders Group
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consortia like the German {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.projekt-deal.de/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Projekt DEAL
}}}
 could provide examples of how to take the first step towards this at a national level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Gaining support from SPARC for any such developments would also be useful.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Particularly for the European area and with a focus on the long tail of science, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.openaire.eu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
OpenAIRE
}}}
 could provide interoperability resolutions to institutional repositories and enhance their outputs visibility.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider the ramifications of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.coalition-s.org/about/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Plan S
}}}
, which aims for full and immediate Open Access to publications from publicly funded research, for your national and local context, and see what can be done to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.coalition-s.org/wp-content/uploads/271118_cOAlitionS_Guidance.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
implement Plan S
}}}
 for your context. Further reading: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://101innovations.wordpress.com/2018/11/30/nine-routes-towards-plan-s-compliance/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Kramer & Bosman, 2018
}}}
\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Support collaborations such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.metadata2020.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Metadata 2020
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.niso.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
NISO
}}}
/{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nist.gov/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
NIST
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://elifesciences.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
eLife
}}}
, to help build a richer connectivity between scholarly communication systems and communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Take action against the privatisation of scholarly works and processes in order to achieve transformation of the publishing industry into one comprised of fair licensing, fair market competition, and under the ownership of the scholarly community.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Develop sustainable, regional and national roadmaps for Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage a wider adoption of preprint and Open Access policies similar to those at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://publicaccess.nih.gov/policy.htm"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
NIH (USA)
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wellcome.ac.uk/funding/guidance/open-access-policy"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Wellcome Trust (UK)
}}}
 and the European Commission.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Encourage research funders to develop calls to support evidence- and theory-based interventions to promote Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fund determinant studies that use behavior change theory to map the determinants of engaging in different Open Scholarship practices\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For example, why do some researchers routinely publish preprints while others do not? Are the arguments produced by researchers opposed to data sharing indeed the reasons why those who do not share data, do not?.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Fund studies that use stakeholder theory to explore ways to achieve more Open Scholarship policies at research and education institutions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To invite all {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.3233/ISU-170839"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
relevant stakeholders
}}}
, including universities, research institutions, learned societies, funders, libraries, and publishers, to collaborate on a transition to open research practices for the benefit of scholarship and society at large.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create showcases/highlights/good practices of Open Scholarship practices on national websites or portals, together with relevant information and resources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab OpenAIRE {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.openaire.eu/contact-noads"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
National Open Access Desks (NOADs)
}}}
 already working on that and could provide input and facilitate communication between all stakeholders towards establishing national guides of sorts.\par}
