{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 3. What is Open Scholarship? \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For more than two decades, the movement for Open Scholarship has evolved from a collection of small, localized efforts to a broad international network of institutions, organizations, governments, practitioners, advocates, and funders. While significant progress has been made on both expanding the understanding and practice of Open Scholarship (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.routledge.com/Virtues-of-Openness-Education-Science-and-Scholarship-in-the-Digital/Peters-Roberts/p/book/9781594516863"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Peters et al., 2012
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1007/s10961-014-9375-6"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Friesike et al., 2013
}}}
; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1038/s41562-016-0021"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Munafo et al., 2017
}}}
), Open Scholarship practices and values are not yet the norm in most research disciplines and adoption is spread {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://knowledgegap.org/index.php/sub-projects/knowledge-and-power-inequality-in-open-science-policies/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
unevenly around the world
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b In this document we consider the term "Open Scholarship" to broadly refer to the process, communication, and re-use of research as practised in any scholarly research discipline, and its inclusion and role within wider society.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The goals and broader vision for Open Scholarship are outlined in foundational documents including the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.budapestopenaccessinitiative.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Budapest Open Access Initiative
}}}
, The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.openarchives.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Archives Initiative
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://viennaprinciples.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Vienna Principles
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.force11.org/scholarly-commons/principles"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Scholarly Commons principles
}}}
, and The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panton_Principles"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Panton Principles
}}}
. Throughout time, there have been dozens of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Declarations_in_support_of_OA"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
declarations
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tinyurl.com/scholcomm-charters"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
charters
}}}
, and statements about the priorities of the various aspects of Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The result of this is that there are now numerous competing, parallel, or overlapping definitions of what Open Scholarship comprises in terms of both research principles and practice, which aim to encapsulate the movement towards fostering scientific growth alongside public accessibility.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Herein, we find it useful to consider Open Scholarship to be analogous to a boundary object {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://journals.openedition.org/rfsic/3220"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Moore, 2017
}}}
, in that it is flexibly adaptive, interpreted differently across communities but with enough immutable content to maintain its integrity. Next to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.routledge.com/Virtues-of-Openness-Education-Science-and-Scholarship-in-the-Digital/Peters-Roberts/p/book/9781594516863"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Peters and Roberts, 2012
}}}
' approach, we find {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-00026-8_2"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Fecher and Friesike, 2013
}}}
's five "schools of thought" to be particularly useful in framing this strategy, based on the components: {\b Infrastructure}, {\b Measurement}, {\b Public}, {\b Democratic} and {\b Pragmatic}. Furthermore, we now extend this to suggest a sixth school of {\b Community and Inclusion}, based on developments in this space in the last 5 years (and more). The OCSD (Open and Collaborative Science in Development) Network has an {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ocsdnet.org/manifesto/open-science-manifesto/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science Manifesto
}}}
 for a more inclusive Open Science for social and environmental well-being that is also highly useful in framing for this strategy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These previous works have been, and remain to be, crucial for building a central identity for the global Open Scholarship community, communicating the case for Open Scholarship to wider society, and providing a basis to push the global movement forward.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To realize the full potential and vision of Open Scholarship, we believe that a document is needed that asks critical questions about the internal structure of Open Scholarship as a movement, and addresses strategic questions about how we, as a global movement, can identify concrete steps to achieving these goals. For those unfamiliar with the language of Open Scholarship, we refer them to the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.righttoresearch.org/resources/openresearchglossary/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Research Glossary
}}}
.\par}
