{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 4. State of the Movement \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.google.de/search?q=Dictionary#dobs=movement"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
movement
}}}
 can be defined as "a group of people working together to advance their shared political, social, or artistic ideas." Open Scholarship supporters are an incredibly diverse group of people, including non-academic citizens, activists, faculty and students at a range of academic or career levels as well as research institutes, scholarly publishers, librarians, policymakers, and Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs). These community members come from countries around the globe and a range of socio-economic situations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As such, Open Scholarship has a range of different social, economic and cultural contexts, which these various communities and stakeholders are united under. While this diversity is a strength for the Open Scholarship movement by bringing a wide variety of perspectives, experiences, capacities, and resources, it also presents challenges for setting strategic directions, building shared plans, and governance and co-ordination structures.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Perhaps the most widespread commonality between Open Scholarship stakeholders is the belief that increased adoption of Open Scholarship practices (and more generally, simply {\i open} practices) is generally a {\i good thing}, and that it would bring wider benefits to the research community, environment, global economies, and wider society.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Given this foundational common value, we can begin to identify the core challenges and opportunities in Open Scholarship to define strategic elements that can be adopted at different levels and by varying stakeholder groups.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 From this, we can gain a collective sense of priority as to the sorts of definitive actions that can be taken to help the advancement of Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.1 Shared Perspectives\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.1.1 General Value Proposition\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Open Scholarship makes research outputs and scholarly practices more accessible and inclusive, and expands our horizons on what is possible from the process of scholarly research.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.1.2 Overall goals and vision\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Research practices and scholarly communications are constantly evolving. However, despite the fact that the Web was originally designed around 30 years ago to disrupt the hierarchical approach of information management by the decentralisation of scholarly communications ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.w3.org/History/1989/proposal.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Berners-Lee, 1989
}}}
), the pervasive spread of the Web has left much of the pre-existing scholarly publication model and industry fundamentally unchanged. Such a perceived slow rate of change or inertia can possibly be attributed to the wide range of diverse stakeholders engaged in this domain, and the deep entrenchment of interests and positions; for example, over copyright, journal brands, and research assessment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As such, one common perspective is that scholarly communication processes need to increasingly embrace the power of Web-native technologies in order to make use of the semantic Web (see e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.semantic-web-journal.net/content/reasonable-semantic-web"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Hitzler, 2010
}}}
 or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/metadata"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Pomerantz, 2015
}}}
) that promises to enhance networking, collaboration, and transparency in research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Alignment of this ideal with the processes of research and education is what is broadly agreed on as Open Scholarship, and there has been an undeniable explosion in the rate of innovation in scholarly communication in this in the last 10 years.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The primary vision here, and one which we are optimistic of achieving, is four-fold:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab {\b That all educational resources and research outputs, as a global societal common good, should be accessible free of charge to all members of the public who wish to benefit from them.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab {\b That such resources should be free from uneccessary constraints on widespread re-use.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab {\b That the benefits of this research should be integrated into the functioning of our wider society.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab {\b That anyone has the right to freely to contribute to, and participate in, this process.}\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.1.3 Definition as a boundary object\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When perceived as a {\i boundary object} ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.lchc.ucsd.edu/MCA/Mail/xmcamail.2012_08.dir/pdfMrgHgzULhA.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Star, 1989
}}}
), Open Scholarship allows us to balance different categories and meanings across many diverse communities of practice. Here, the creation and management of such boundary objects is a key process in developing and maintaining coherence across intersecting communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Broadly, the core aspects of Open Scholarship can be divided into two major categories: {\b knowledge and practices} and {\b principles and values}. For the former, this relates to aspects such as Open Access, Open Data, and Open Evaluation. The core principles or values of Open Scholarship include participation, equality, transparency, cognitive justice, collaboration, sharing, equity, and inclusivity; aspects that are often missing from many 'traditional' forms of scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Generally, it is agreed upon that the combination of these practices and principles will result in a better (i.e., more rigorous or fairer) research process, all grouped under the broad heading of Open Scholarship. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1186/s13059-015-0669-2"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Watson (2015)
}}}
 notes that these attributes are not exclusive to Open Scholarship, but should be key traits of good science in general.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, we acknowledge that Open Scholarship is not a simple construct to understand for many at the present, and often even has its own language. We fully acknowledge that such a barrier must be overcome in order to maximise participation and engagement with both the principles and the practices ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.7287/peerj.preprints.2689v1"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Masuzzo and Martens, 2017
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.slideshare.net/OpenAIRE_eu/peer-review-in-the-age-of-open-science"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Tony Ross-Hellauer (2017). Principles of Open Scholarship. Slideshare
}}}
. (CC BY).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.1.4 Open Scholarship ecosystem\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Four major elements exist as preconditions to Open Scholarship adoption:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab {\b Users}: Awareness of Open Scholarship to engage with the practices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab {\b Process}: Open Scholarship tools that guide adoption of practices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab {\b Context}: Community and systemic support to create a sustainable Open Scholarship environment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab {\b Incentives}: Motivations to engage with the practices.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \par}
