Foster Open Scholarship Taxonomy
}}}
 (CC BY 4.0). {\i Please note that this is a non-exhaustive taxonomy of all possible aspects of Open Science & Scholarship.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.2 Varied Perspectives\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As well as these shared commonalities above, tensions also exist between the best way to adopt Open Scholarship practices. Open Scholarship is an agenda with multiple stakeholders (or groups), whose diverse cultures, backgrounds and interests mean that one-size-fits-all solutions could potentially harm local interests (or vice versa).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 On the other hand, there is a need to ensure that strategies are joined-up so that the actions of those with similar aims are not working at cross-purposes. Such "fault-lines" for the creation of a cohesive strategy include geographic, disciplinary, and stakeholder specificities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.2.1 Geographic specificities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Hundreds of individual {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Advocacy_organizations_for_OA"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
initiatives and organisations
}}}
 already exist to help provide and promote Open Access at different levels around the world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Thousands of individual {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://oerworldmap.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
initiatives and organisations
}}}
 already exist to help provide and promote Open Education at different levels around the world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab High costs associated with some Open Access publishing actively discriminate against researchers from Low and Middle Income Countries (LMICs).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Many popular indexing services, such as Scopus and Web of Science, are explicitly biased against journals from developing countries, or those that do not have English as the primary language ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1007/s11192-015-1765-5"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Mongeon and Paul-Hus, 2016
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It needs to be ensured that any narrative of Open Scholarship integrates the diverse world-views, experiences, and challenges of Latin America, Asia, Africa and the Middle East, as outlined in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ocsdnet.org/manifesto/open-science-manifesto/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open and Collaborative Science Manifesto
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.2.2 Disciplinary specificities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab As the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=2004-01-01%202018-12-28&q=open%20scholarship,open%20science"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
more widely-used
}}}
 term Open Science contains the word 'Science', this can have an adverse effect of excluding researchers from the arts, humanities, engineering, mathematics, and other fields that might not be considered to be science. This problem seems mainly confined to native-English speaking researchers, since in many other languages, the word that is used for science (e.g., Wissenschaft in German) is more general than in English. Other terms such as e-Research and Digital Humanities describe similar practices across different communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Differences in attitudes towards, and rates of uptake of, different Open practices. For example, many open scientific practices are geared towards more empirical and quantitative research, and therefore require different evaluation and incentive structures than other scholarly disciplines.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Accounting for domain-specific issues. For example, accounting for variation in biological supplies from different laboratory companies is a significant issue in reproducibility for biological research. Open Access books are a major problem in the Humanities ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://dx.doi.org/10.1017/CBO9781316161012"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Eve, 2014
}}}
), but less so in STEM, and are often sidelined as an issue as a result.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab At the present there are few preprints from the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openpharma.blog/2017/08/14/when-will-preprints-take-off-in-medicine/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
pharmaceutical industry
}}}
, and none covering primary clinical data. There are at present considerable barriers to preprints of industry work, including the possibility of material that has not yet been peer-reviewed being seen as promotional, and the possibility of readers changing clinical practice based on material that has not yet been peer-reviewed, however well labelled a preprint is.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The pharmaceutical industry, which funds {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/185198"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
approximately half of all medical research
}}}
, is becoming aware of the potential for many aspects of open scholarship to improve the transparency, accessibility and speed of reporting its research. In this highly regulated, compliance-focused industry, which presents a substantial source of revenue to publishers, there are additional barriers to change beyond those discussed in the academic community. The benefits and barriers to new ways of working are now {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openpharma.blog/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
being examined
}}}
 and changes are taking place.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Most notably, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.shire.com/en/newsroom/2018/january/xajhds"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
one pharma company
}}}
 has mandated that all its research should be published open access from January 2018, although not necessarily CC BY, and a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ipsen.com/ipsen-commits-to-making-all-its-published-scientific-research-freely-accessible-to-everyone/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
second pharma company
}}}
 has followed suit in January 2019. One other {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.21305/ISMPPEU2018.001"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
has mandated that all their internal research staff
}}}
 should use ORCID when publishing their work.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab There are few preprints on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openpharma.blog/2018/05/31/what-do-preprints-mean-for-medical-publishing/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
bioRxiv from the pharmaceutical industry
}}}
, although uptake is increasing in line with growth in preprinting of non-commercial medical research, and very few covering primary clinical data. There are at present considerable barriers to preprints of industry-funded work, including the possibility of material that has not yet been peer-reviewed being seen as promotional, and the possibility of readers changing clinical practice based on material that has not yet been peer-reviewed, however well labelled a preprint is. Issues such as these have delayed the launch of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://yoda.yale.edu/medrxiv"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
MedRxiv
}}}
, a preprint server aimed specifically at medical research.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 4.2.3 Stakeholder specificities\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Consider the range of stakeholders who have a direct interest in the development of Open Scholarship - researchers, students, funders, librarians, research managers, scholarly societies, infrastructure providers, industry, wider society, publishers and other service providers, educators, NGOs, and policymakers. Each of these groups engage in the Open Scholarship agenda for different reasons, and often these goals will be in conflict/tension depending on their intrinsic motivations, understanding, and goals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, regarding Open Access, there is little consensus on the best way forward for this at a multitude of scales (geographic, institutional, individual). The result of such ongoing tensions is, perhaps not surprisingly, the lack of well-defined strategic priorities for Open Access Conflicts between different stakeholder groups can often be distinguished based on competing interests, which filter through at multiple levels in communication, policy, and practices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The result of this is that the relationship network of stakeholders engaged in scholarly communication, and in particular developments in Open Scholarship, is particularly complex. Some of the most highly debated points include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Appropriate licensing schemes for research data;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Where funding for scholarly publishing activities should come from;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Who should be in charge of scholarly research infrastructure;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The role of policy mandates in driving openness;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab What the optimal model of Open Access should be, and what the traits of this are;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The role of charities, non-profit, and for-profit players; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab How to resolve conflicts between different stakeholders.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is a non-exhaustive list, but highlights that conflict resolution in scholarly communication can come in a range of flavours, based around key issues such as academic freedom, governance structures, and financing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 4.3 Extent of Open Scholarship adoption to consider the movement successful\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are varied opinions, and a lack of consensus, around what extent of Open Scholarship adoption is necessary to constitute success. Part of this is due to the lack of well-defined objectives, which means that defining a pathway with clear cut stepping stones has been difficult, and remained clouded by the different competing stakeholders and multiplicity of complex processes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, some aspects are clear, which can be generally agreed upon by all stakeholders as being optimal results of Open Scholarship:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Transforming the present scholarly communications market so that it flips to Open Scholarship services as the default model for research processes and outputs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Shifting public funding models to pay for the dissemination of services and outputs, rather than individual copies/subscriptions of content.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Providing sufficiently high quality and diversity of services to permit adequate choice for researchers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mainstreaming Open Scholarship so that it competes with traditional processes, in terms of reach, uptake, and incentivisation and reward.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Building a significant number of education, training and support systems based on Open Scholarship skills development.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Replacing entire traditional research workflows by Open Scholarship methodologies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Phasing out proprietary software in favour of free and Open Source software.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Measurably increasing quality of research and achievement that leads to greater career prospects, and social, academic, and economic growth and innovation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adoption of complete Open Access by funding agencies; policies that explicitly allow use of preprints and other pre-publications in funding applications, as well as consideration of non-traditional research outputs.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 5. Top Strategic Priorities for Open Scholarship \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Taking into account the strategic goals and success criteria listed above, it is possible to define several leading sub-domains of actions that need to be implemented in order to achieve them. While there is no apparent consensus on this from the Open Scholarship movement, or what the priority order is, there is a general agreement that all of these actions are, at least to some degree, important.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These strategic sub-domains are adapted from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-00026-8_2"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Fecher and Friesike (2013)
}}}
, and form the foundation for the full {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#Strategy"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\b strategy}
}}}
 outlined above.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.1 Democratization \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Believing that there is an unequal distribution of access to knowledge, Open Scholarship is concerned with making scholarly knowledge outputs (including publications, code, methods, and data) accessible and available freely for everyone with access to modern technology (e.g., a computer and Internet connection). This is especially the case for publicly-funded research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Importantly, democracy in Open Scholarship means not only equal access to knowledge, but also equal possibilities to contribute to knowledge and equal rights to participate in the world-wide community's decisions that affect knowledge creation and distribution.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The latter means that Open Scholarship is antithetical to closed power clubs which are limited to a small number of participants deciding for the whole international community, whether such closed clubs are supported by institutional/governmental funders or are bottom-up organisations (e.g., small groups of prestigious authors).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Indeed, it is quite unlikely that more than 10 million scholars, highly educated and intelligent, would agree with some rules created for them by a small number of people (or even worse, by some groups with financial interest). A more likely scenario is that the new rules governing Open Scholarship will appear in the open debate, through many collective projects, just like how this strategy was formed through collective editing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Several specific mechanisms have been recently proposed to realise democratic values in Open Scholarship in a decentralised way, including peer-to-peer and blockchain-based mechanisms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In working towards principles of Open Scholarship, we acknowledge that there is the potential for complexity, or even conflict in our objectives as policies and working practices evolve. Awareness of the broader research, industry and education landscape will help to position Open Scholarship to have the greatest possible impact, and to mitigate the potential of other policies and priorities to limit its potential.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, copyright proposals in the EU that would limit who is permitted to undertake TDM (text and data mining), or policies promoting intellectual property (IP) and commercialisation should be balanced with policies that permit a wide range of uses of data, research, and knowledge. There do exist a number of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.communia-association.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
recent
}}}
 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://fixcopyright.eu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
initiatives
}}}
 working towards the development of copyright frameworks that help the Open Scholarship cause.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Other specific aspects include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "bit.ly/oa-book"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Access
}}}
 publishing that allows not only free to read access but also free to reuse and free to distribute to the widest possible extent. Many believe that access to scientific knowledge is a fundamental human right.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One of the strongest arguments for Open Access is that publicly (or taxpayer) funded research should be accessible to the public. The increasing private sector funding of research is a difficult aspect to reconcile with this view at the present.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Licences, licensing, and rights waivers for copyright that are understandable by both humans and machines. Typically, this has been administered through some combination of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://creativecommons.org/faq/#what-does-it-mean-that-creative-commons-licenses-are-machine-readable"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Creative Commons
}}}
 and Open Source licensing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Moving away from patenting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab One example of the open approach to patent management is "weak licensing - strong certification" - a situation especially easy to apply in medicine, where therapeutic devices or compounds are weakly licensed in terms of patents but the requirements for entering the market are set high from the regulator.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Recognising the value of open source and open scholarship in accelerating innovation and research discovery (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1038/nchem.1149"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Woelfle et al., 2011
}}}
; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pmed.1002276"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Balasegaram et al., 2017
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Changing publishing norms to make all objects within a research output to be concordant with the FAIR principles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Making software and code readily available, re-usable, citable, and formally recognised as a research output, along with research articles, data, and metadata.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wider use of data repositories and data journals for sharing research outputs, without restrictions. This enables data to be re-used by others in ways that are either foreseen or unforeseen by the original creators.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab As one of the greatest difficulties for compliance with this is the amount of extra effort perceived in making work shareable in a compliant manner, automated or low-barrier methods of dissemination will be critical here.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research material repositories and the sharing of physical research outputs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research material sharing is critical for issues of reproducibility, reducing redundancy, and promoting open scientific collaboration. Issues here were empirically examined by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://creativecommons.org/about/program-areas/open-science/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Science Commons
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sharing well-curated and annotated materials within communities without restrictive licensing or complex material transfer agreements which slow scientific progress due to complex legal jargon or stringent terms and conditions.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Streamlined Material Transfer Agreements (MTAs) and Open Scholarship Trust Agreements (OSTAs) - legal agreement templates which may be easily amended for any researcher, irrespective of discipline, at any institution to simply share almost all categories of research materials they generate in the course of their research allowing efficient, open and collaborative scientific practices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Principles described herein "The core feature of trusts\u8212-holding property for the benefit of others is well suited to constructing a research community that treats reagents as public goods." {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1126/scitranslmed.aai9055"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Edwards et al (2017)
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab E.g. OSTA template: {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.thesgc.org/click-trust"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
SGC
}}}
 "click-trust" agreement E.g. MTA (Material Transfer Agreement) templates through {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://creativecommons.org/about/program-areas/open-science/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Science Commons
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab OER (Open Educational Resources). For more on this, see the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.oerstrategy.org/home/read-the-doc/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Foundations for OER Strategy Development
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.2 Pragmatism and transparency \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Following the principle that the creation of knowledge is made more efficient through collaboration and strengthened through critique, Open Scholarship seeks to harness network effects by connecting scholars and making scholarly processes at all levels transparent.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Such optimisation can be achieved through modularising the process of knowledge creation, opening the scientific value chain, integrating external knowledge sources and collective intelligence, and facilitating collaboration through online tools and platforms. This sort of openness in the research process itself represents a paradigm shift from the traditional closed and independent nature of research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Additional key aspects include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Making the process behind research should be {\i as transparent as possible, and as closed as necessary} (for example, in order to protect sensitive data).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Reproducibility ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.1421412111"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Leek and Peng, 2015
}}}
; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1101/066803"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Patil et al., 2016
}}}
), enhanced by increased transparency of research processes themselves, and not just outputs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Includes core aspects such as open methodologies, access to research tools for open work, as well as more transparent research workflows around preprints and open peer review.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This can help to resolve ongoing "reproducibility crises" in medicine, psychology, economics, and sociology.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Researchers should aim to automatically generate the results in a research paper through appropriately documented data and code. A range of Web 2.0 tools now exist to make this as simple as possible.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Replicability, to obtain the similar conclusions from new experiments, observations, and analyses based on a previously published manuscript.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Sustainability of research through increased access to expertise, collaboration, knowledge aggregation, and enhanced productivity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Being able to durably test results within a paper over time, which would include data archiving and software longevity and versioning.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Benefaction, by starting from and expanding someone workflow/codebase/tools, and avoiding unnecessary duplication of technical tasks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adoption of the huge array of Web 2.0 technologies for communication and collaboration, which help to facilitate increasing demands for higher productivity and research complexity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Much of this is dependent on the willingness of researchers themselves to contribute to scholarly research in an open, collaborative, and collective manner.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Motivation for this is largely down to whether such researchers perceive this process as being advantageous to them in some way, for example getting a return on investment in social capital or prestige.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Many tools to facilitate and accelerate scientific discovery, and enhance the research process already exist in some form.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This includes social networking sites, electronic laboratory notebooks, data archives, online collaboration services, controlled vocabularies and ontologies, and other research sharing platforms.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A key element of their design is to help researchers improve what they are already doing, through efficiency, rather than designing them in mind of what researchers should be doing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Disruption beyond this structure, and the close association of research practices to finalised products based around research papers, is unlikely to catalyse change. This is due to the lack of intrinsic motivation of researchers to commit to processes that do not offer them a reciprocal gain in social capital.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.3 Infrastructure \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Achieving the full benefits of Open Scholarship requires platforms, tools and services for dissemination and collaboration. Such technical infrastructure can be built with current off-shelf technologies and at a much lower cost than traditional publishing methods.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Presently, there is a general lack of funding and support for critical existing aspects of open scholarly infrastructure, despite its clear role in defining particular research practices and workflows. More recently, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://jrost.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Joint Roadmap for Open Science Tools
}}}
 launched as a community-driven approach to help resolve this.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Examples of existing infrastructure include the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doaj.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
DOAJ
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
arXiv
}}}
 including domain-specific variants such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://socarxiv.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
socArXiv
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://hcommons.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Humanities Commmons
}}}
, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://osf.io/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science Framework
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sherpa.ac.uk/romeo/index.php"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Sherpa/RoMEO
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://orcid.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ORCID
}}}
, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://opensciencefoundation.eu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science Foundation
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pkp.sfu.ca/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Public Knowledge Project
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theoj.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Journals
}}}
 and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://okfn.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Knowledge Foundation
}}}
, among many others, which offer crucial services to a range of stakeholders. Without sustainable funding sources, these services remain vulnerable to either collapse, or being acquired by players in the private sector, an increasingly common occurrence.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To reduce the risk of infrastructure collapse, and to increase its capacity, continued funder support is required for any sort of sustainable scholarly infrastructure (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1101/110825"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Anderson et al., 2017
}}}
). A proportion of research funder budgets should be allocated to support this (e.g., 2%), and initiatives such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://scoss.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
SCOSS
}}}
 and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.orfg.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Research Funders Group
}}}
 should be fully supported in this regard.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This includes elements such as:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Standards and Persistent Identifiers (PIDs);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Shared services, including abstracting/indexing services and research data (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doaj.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
DOAJ
}}}
);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Support and dissemination services (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sherpa.ac.uk/romeo/index.php"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
SHERPA/RoMEO
}}}
);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Repository services (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.coar-repositories.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
COAR
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://v2.sherpa.ac.uk/opendoar/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
OpenDOAR
}}}
);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Publishing services (e.g., arXiv, hcommons, Open Journals);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Collaboration platforms and tools (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://osf.io/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
the Open Science Framework
}}}
);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Automation of open practices ("open by default");\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open citation services building upon ORCID and CrossRef initiatives (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://opencitations.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
opencitations
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://i4oc.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
I4OC
}}}
);\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Social Virtual Research Environments (SVREs), to facilitate the management and sharing of research objects, provide the incentives for Open Scholarship, integrate existing software and tools, and provide the actual platform for conducting of research;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Interoperability of services (e.g., based on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/sdata201618"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
FAIR principles
}}}
); and,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Semantic web technology: metadata, harvesting, exchange services (see e.g. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Open_Metadata_Handbook"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
the Open Metadata Handbook
}}}
).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Perhaps the best way to regard infrastructure is as existing interactive technologies that you do not really notice until they cease to work as they should. For example, automated and integrated data sharing without individual submissions to fragmented online data repositories.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ultimately, what we might want to achieve with such infrastructures is a streamlined process of large-scale, data-intensive research, operated collaboratively through high-performance computer clusters that transcend all geographical, technical, and disciplinary boundaries.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The potential social aspects of such services means that there is additional scope for a range of purposes, including networking, marketing and promotion, non-academic information exchange, and discussion forums.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.4 Public good \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Based on the recognition that true societal impact requires societal engagement in research and readily understandable communication of scientific results, Open Scholarship seeks to bring the public to collaborate in research through community science.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Web 2.0 technologies are fully capable of helping to make scholarship more readily understandable through non-specialist summaries, blogging, and other less formal communicative methods. Here, societal impact (e.g., a better understanding of the world) should not be a secondary or niche consideration for research, but rather an intrinsic part of it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Much of this relates to the changing role of a researcher within a modern, digital society, and distils down to two main aspects:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab The influence that the wider public can have on the intrinsic research process; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab The understanding of that research by a wider non-specialist audiences, including effective ways of communicating research.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Key aspects here include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Removing barriers to research based on race, gender, income, status, geography, or any other demographic factors.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Removing barriers based on access to funding.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Inclusion of dispersed, external individuals from beyond those within traditional non-digital spheres as an active role in research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Community science (also known as Citizen Science) and involving society in research priority setting.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This also opens up opportunities for crowd-funding of research projects, a presently little-explored aspect of the public school.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Constant and continuous documentation and sharing all research outputs created during an exposed research lifecycle, from lab notebooks used during the project to methods, materials, algorithms, data, code and the paper.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This helps to prepare research for greater digestion and comprehension from the wider community, and in particular non-specialist interested parties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Leveraging public spaces and infrastructure such as public libraries, museums, art galleries, and schools.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.5 Measurement \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To shift the behaviour of academics it is necessary to change how they are measured; to change how they are measured means new metrics that reflect different values and more diverse forms of scientific impact; see, for example the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://responsiblemetrics.org/the-metric-tide/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Metric Tide report
}}}
 or the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ec.europa.eu/research/openscience/pdf/report.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
EU report on Next-generation metrics
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Ironically perhaps, the usage of advanced metrics and analytics for research assessment is in its relative infancy within the halls of academia. Practically, finding a way to integrate a research openness metric into University Ranking system algorithms would embed openness values into policy and align measures with core open values.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An alternative, which does not seem too appealing to many, would be to do away with any form of measurement, which often is considered to be bad for the progress of scientific research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There is a widespread acknowledgement that traditional metrics for measuring scientific impact have proven problematic, for example by being too heavily focused on journal publications or inappropriately applied at the journal-level. The most notorious example is the Journal Impact Factor, an average citation metric across journals that is often inappropriately used at the article- and individual-level, and also confines assessment to journal-based research outputs, thereby discriminating against innovative forms of research assessment ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://arxiv.org/abs/1801.08992"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Lariviere and Sugimoto, 2018
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Open Scholarship seeks "{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Altmetrics"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
alternative metrics
}}}
" (also known broadly as altmetrics; not to be confused with the company, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.altmetric.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Altmetric
}}}
) that can make use of the new possibilities of digitally networked tools to track and measure the impact of scholarship through formerly invisible activities. These include social shares, tagging, bookmarks, addition to collections, readerships, comments and discussion, ratings, and usage or citation in non-journal formats, all of which build the {\i context} of a research object.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Importantly, these capture new forms of information about the dissemination of research, as well as the process of collaboration, which help to expand the traditional view of publication being the end of a narrow research pipeline.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, the principles of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://responsiblemetrics.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\i responsible metrics}
}}}
 use are closely aligned with the goals of Open Scholarship:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Robustness}: Basing metrics on the best possible data in terms of accuracy and scope;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Humility}: Recognising that quantitative evaluation should support - but not supplant - qualitative, expert assessment;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Transparency}: Keeping data collection and analytical processes open and transparent, so that those being evaluated can test and verify the results;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Diversity}: Accounting for variation by field, and using a range of indicators to reflect and support a plurality of research and researcher career paths across the system;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\b Reflexivity}: Recognising and anticipating the systemic and potential effects of indicators, and updating them in response.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Along with this, measurement play a core role in the future of Open Scholarship through:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Changing norms of research evaluation from traditional metrics, to a more rigorous, evidence-based, and diverse/holistic suite of sources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Stop using the Journal Impact Factor in any form, and commit to the principles and practices outlined in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sfdora.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
San Francisco Declaration on Research Assessment
}}}
 (DORA), and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.leidenmanifesto.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Leiden Manifesto
}}}
, and a fairer, more objective and robust system of research evaluation.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Consider alternative metrics, including those explicitly designed to measure openness ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1002/asi.23741"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Nichols and Twidale, 2017
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab See also the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://humetricshss.org/about/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Humane Metrics Initiative
}}}
 and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.metrics-toolkit.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Metrics Toolkit
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Investigate the potential utility of a wide range of potential research evaluation sources, including pre-registrations, registered reports, those regarding software, materials, and data, and also public outreach efforts and citizen science.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Science-based assessment: experimentation before implementation of any metric, in order to better understand the scope, biases, and constraints of any quantitative measures.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Issues of transparency and reproducibility apply both to scholarship itself and to the mechanisms through which our research is measured (e.g., whether a metric can be independently reproduced). {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.jonathanfurner.info/docs/furnerInPress-a.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Furner, 2014
}}}
 provides an ethical framework for bibliometrics, which can be generalised to broader sets of metrics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Of course, there are also dangers with new metrics, since {\i all} metrics {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goodhart's_law"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
can and will be gamed
}}}
, and new metrics offer new, little understood opportunities for gaming. New metrics will also not solve the publish or perish problem, but only transfer it. There is thus also a strong role for qualitative evaluation procedures in the future of research assessment.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 5.6 Community and inclusion \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Motivated by the acknowledgement that scholarship requires all voices to be heard, and the involvement of a committed community of actors, Open Scholarship seeks to ensure diversity and inclusion are key principles in scholarly conversations. This factor is touched upon in the other schools defined by Fecher and Frieseke (2013), but based on discussion and events since this publication, we feel merits a separate section here to highlight its importance.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Here, key aspects include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Diversity and inclusivity.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The definition of diversity is complex and multi-dimensional, but here generally means encouraging tolerance and inclusion of people from a range of different backgrounds. This includes dimensions of ethnicity and culture, psychography, geography, ability, geodiversity, neurodiversity, and other demographic aspects.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It is the responsibility of the wider Open Scholarship community to build awareness that community diversity and inclusivity are fundamental principles.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This includes developing tools and techniques to fix existing issues; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Creating and disseminating research resources.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Community cohesion and messaging must be a foundational principle for the Open Scholarship community, and extended to all other related communities. As part of this, the community must:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Develop and practice appropriate standards;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Create educational curricula for practitioners;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Obtain public goods and public funding;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Collaborate with other related or overlapping communities, including Open Science Hardware and Open Source Software, on common areas of interest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Community science (also known as Citizen Science) (also mentioned in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "#Public"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Public good
}}}
), including:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Tackling community-driven megaprojects;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Spill-over effects to and from education; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Strengthening the ability to participate intellectually, donate computing power, biological samples or other resources, including money (crowdfunded research), towards research projects.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 6. Movement Strengths \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This section of the strategy will describe some of the strengths of the Open Scholarship 'movement'; or perhaps more appropriately, 'community'.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Organisational structure and collective impact}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The global scholarly community is vast, covering every continent, and embedded within strong research and academic institutes. The 'Open' movement goes beyond just scholarship, and is related to wider fields such as Open Culture, Open Government, Open Source, and Open Society. Therefore, the potential collective impact that the movement can have is enormous, with ramifications for global society; for example, influencing the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.unfoundation.org/features/globalgoals/the-global-goals.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
UN Sustainable Development Goals
}}}
.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Scholarship activism as part of a broader Open movement is benefiting from cross-collaborations with advocates from across different sectors. For example, now Open Scholarship is often seen as a gateway to Open Education, but has policies strengthened by experiences from the Open Source movement.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Diverse participation of passionate individuals}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Significant successes in Open Scholarship are often attributed to passionate, persevering champions, particularly in the policy and advocacy/adoption arenas. These individuals demonstrate a great capacity to achieve substantial changes, and create strong influences, almost single-handedly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab As an asset to the movement, they become especially important when their experiences and knowledge can be shared and multiplied, through building of collaborations, networks and communities, and mentorship models.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Strength of research and evidence supporting Open Scholarship practices}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab There is an increasingly strong case now supporting almost all aspects of Open Scholarship. Some key summaries of this work include {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.7554/eLife.16800"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
McKiernan et al., 2016
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.12688/f1000research.8460.3"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Tennant et al., 2016
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pbio.1002614"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
McKiernan, 2017
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.12688/f1000research.17425.1"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Katz et al., 2018
}}}
. The impact of this can be seen at multiple levels, from the practices of individuals, up to national-level policies around Open Access and Open Scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Key projects, groups, and scholars have been conducting research into various aspects of Open Scholarship and its impacts, finding them to be almost overwhelmingly positive. As the movement grows, the evidence base, and the depth of critical analysis will continue to develop and mature.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Breadth of creativity in coming up with technical and sociotechnical solutions}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For example, 'green' and 'gold' routes to Open Access. The former relates to self-archiving, and the latter to publishing in an Open Access journal. While some variations exist (e.g., diamond, bronze, platinum OA), these models generally transcend geographical, institutional, or sectoral variations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The growth and adoption of preprints as a method of getting research out sooner and more transparently. In the last two years, this has led to a rapidly evolving {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.31222/osf.io/796tu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
landscape
}}}
 around preprints, with technological innovation and community practices constantly adapting.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Availability of Open Scholarship charters and declarations}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This ever-growing range of high-level statements in support of openness (typically {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://oad.simmons.edu/oadwiki/Declarations_in_support_of_OA"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Access
}}}
), but also {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://tinyurl.com/scholcomm-charters"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
more broadly
}}}
, offers internally consistent sets of goals and actions that are result of a lot of thinking and discussing.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Strong push to develop policy models}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This transpires from a combination of dynamic, broad and cohesive top-down (policy initiatives from funders, governments, institutions) and bottom-up (grassroots) approaches. It remains important that the imperative and agenda for Open Scholarship remains recognised at the highest political levels.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The UK House of Commons Science and Technology {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/science-and-technology-committee/news-parliament-2017/research-integrity3-evidence-17-19/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Committee into research integrity
}}}
 or thefunder-driven {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.coalition-s.org/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
cOAlition S
}}}
 are excellent examples of this.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 One issue with top-down policies is that bodies such as governments and funders demand researchers to comply with rules about data sharing, open code, and the like, yet do not always provide the resources or structures necessary for compliant behaviour.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Bottom-up policies weave together best-practices from existing scientific research communities and, compared to top-down approaches, are more often voluntary than mandatory. Evaluating the degree of alignment between top-down and bottom-up policies might help to illustrate how both approaches can better accommodate and promote Open Scholarship together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Diversity of goals enables progress on many fronts simultaneously}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If one considers the breadth of aspects that fall under Open Scholarship (e.g., Open Access, Open Evaluation, Open Data, Open Source, Citizen Science), and the enormous diversity of organisations and individuals pushing these forward, then it is possible to scope the shifting landscape of the movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Making sure that these efforts are more linked up in the future will be critical for parallel progression.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Geographical heterogeneity and variably successful initiatives}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab For example, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.scielo.org/php/index.php?lang=en"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Scientific Electronic Library Online
}}}
 (SciELO) has proven unequivocally successful across Latin America, Portugal, and South Africa. Similarly, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ajol.info/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Africa Journals Online
}}}
 (AJOL) has become very popular in Africa.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Scholarship has been recognised by key international organisations active in research and education, and has strong support from institutes around the world.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Scholarship tends to have a common language (English, usually) for ease of understanding (although see below for why this can also be a challenge).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Accessibility, user-friendliness, and dissemination}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The Open Scholarship movement publishes articles and resources that are typically free, well-indexed by Google and other search engines, easy to read on mobile devices, and quick to make use of graphics and multimedia to illustrate points. This tendency to embrace technology helps the Open Scholarship movement disseminate its ideas more broadly and quickly than can be accomplished by traditional publication methods.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Corresponding practices such as the active use of platform-independent text formatting (i.e. via markdown), the provision of well-formed document structures via clearly-labelled headings, paragraphs, etc., and a pro-active assignment of alt-texts for images and descriptive information for graphs, videos, etc. does not only help making information machine-readable, which is needed for properly disseminating information via the semantic web, but also has the added benefit of making this information accessible for people with access needs (see e.g. the basic accessibility guidelines provided by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/UKHomeOffice/posters/blob/master/accessibility/dos-donts/posters_en-UK/accessibility-posters-set.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
UK Home Office Digital
}}}
).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 7. Movement Challenges \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These challenges represent potential focal points of future discussion, research, and policy development. They include both external conditions in the greater research ecosystem, and internal conditions that exist within the Open Scholarship movement. Not all challenges are equal, or present in every potential context or community. However, the following highlights frequently spear in discussions about Open Scholarship strategy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.1 External conditions \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Reconciling private interests}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There is currently little consensus over whether the future of Open Scholarship should be purely owned by non-profit entities governed by the global scholarly community (including charities and NGOs), or whether there is a space for private or corporate interests.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is likely that the future will be a mixed model combining all actor types, although the relative position, power, and status of these remains to be seen. Further discussion is needed here to overcome the widespread inertia where current business models are concerned. This includes:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Overcoming the misconception that Open Scholarship is anti-commercial/demonstrating return on investment (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pmed.1002276"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Balasegaram et al., 2017
}}}
; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1136/bmjopen-2017-015997"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Hakoum et al., 2017
}}}
).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Resolving frictions between a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.force11.org/group/scholarly-commons-working-group"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Scholarly Commons
}}}
 model for research, and its operation within a capitalistic framework. (e.g., {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://danielskatzblog.wordpress.com/2016/10/25/clash-of-cultures-why-all-science-isnt-open-science/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Clash of cultures
}}}
)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Seeking development of alternative business models, such as the consortium approach of the Open Library of Humanities ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.16995/olh.46"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Eve and Edwards, 2015
}}}
).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Political agendas}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Open Scholarship is characterized by numerous competing, parallel, and overlapping definitions in principles and practices. Accordingly, governments, public and private funding agencies, research institutes, and educational entities continually develop diverse policies to govern Open Scholarship initiatives.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 These policies span countries, scientific disciplines, and components of the Open Scholarship ecosystem, and impose rules, regulations, and guidelines upon the scientific research community via mechanisms including government policies, grant funding requirements, and institutional mandates.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ec.europa.eu/research/openscience/index.cfm"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science
}}}
 has been a high priority on the EU agenda for some time. The primary focus of this has, however, been on economic growth, development, and innovation. The core academic and social aspects of Open Scholarship appear to have been somewhat under-discussed.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Other nations have been generally slow in adopting national Open Science policies or strategies. However, in July 2018, France launched their {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://libereurope.eu/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/SO_A4_2018_05-EN_print.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
National Plan for Open Science
}}}
, and the Netherlands also have a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.openscience.nl/en/open-science-in-the-netherlands"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
National Plan for Open Science
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab In France, the focus was on benefits to research, education, the economy and innovation, and society. In the Netherlands, the focus appears to be more on opening up research to collaborate on social and technological issues. In Estonia, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.etag.ee/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/Open-Science-in-Estonia-Principles-and-Recommendations-final.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Science
}}}
 appears to be more based on public access rights, improving the quality of research and collaboration, and increased social and economic impact.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab EU Horizon 2020 is one of the most notable government initiatives involving Open Scholarship policies (see also work on 'Plan S'). For example, the Responsible Research and Innovation (RRI) component of the Work Programme "Science with and for Society" makes open education, research, and access explicit targets of EU policy.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The FASTR Act, Open Government Data Act, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sourcecode.cio.gov/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Federal Source Code Policy
}}}
; Affordable College Textbook Act; U.S. National Cancer Moonshot Initiative; Dept of Education Open Licensing Rule; Executive Directive on Public Access; California Taxpayer Access to Publicly Funded Research Act; and Illinois Open Access to Articles Act are all examples of policy changes in the USA that fall under the umbrella of Open Scholarship'.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 From these examples, it is clear that there is a general lack of synthesized and consistent strategy on the political motivations for Open Scholarship. Deeper coordination is needed in this field to strategically identify which aspects of Open Scholarship match with each intended political outcome.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Researcher awareness and apathy}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Awareness of Open Scholarship is still often very low among certain research communities. This is true in the understanding that Open Scholarship exists as a way of increasing standard research workflow efficiency (not as a direct alternative), and the benefits of doing so.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Some researchers may adopt Open Scholarship practices (e.g., data sharing, Open Access publishing), while hesitate to equate their practices with the term Open Scholarship. Even where awareness levels are high, this does not necessarily translate into adoption, often due to a lack of information, sufficient incentives and motivation, or interest.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The fact that researchers might adopt open scholarship practices based on pragmatic reasons, but don't use the label or identify it as open scholarship, or that they are open scholars, requires further empirical investigation as one of the key social aspects of the movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The heterogeneous geographical reach and awareness of Open Scholarship practices needs to be investigated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This relates to communications issues around Open Scholarship being a unique concept to 'traditional' scholarship, rather than just enhancement of the process and communication.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Language and appearance of community}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open scholarship must be better promoted in non-English languages. The hegemony of English often works to further empower Global North countries in such conversations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The most influential scientists got their position by being successful in 'closed' system. This bias is powerful in defining research practices of early career researchers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Misleading uses of Open Scholarship terminologies dilutes the intended messages. So-called 'open washing' refers to using the Open Scholarship terms for products, services, and practices that are hardly open. For example, free is not open, and simply providing research tools is not open either. This also includes confusing Open Scholarship with Open Access.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab There is an imminent danger that some companies with a history of anti-openness can move into and co-opt the Open scholarship movement, if this is not appropriately defined and adhered to.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The Open movement is beset by communication and engagement challenges, including from powerful players with opposing or divergent interests. The community should adopt the stance of 'radical kindness' when engaging with those actors, and treat them with absolute, unwavering civility; in particular, when those common courtesies are not repaid to them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Scholarship does come with its own set of technical terms. To lower engagement thresholds, avoid the use of jargon where possible, and make sure commonly used terms are defined with precision. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openresearchglossary.herokuapp.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Research Glossary
}}}
 could be useful here.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Copyright}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Legal (copyright/licensing) and economic (ownership/business models) knowledge may be as important as technical knowledge. This is something though that is generally poorly understood or appreciated within scholarly communities.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Underestimating the power of copyright laws, and the intersection this has with various aspects of Open Scholarship, may have been one of the key reasons why the Open movement has not met {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://poynder.blogspot.com/2017/02/copyright-immoveable-barrier-that-open.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
some of its principle objectives
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The Open Scholarship Movement may be able to draw valuable lessons from the experience of the international Open Education movement - and in particular from the actors involved in the introduction of Open Educational Resources (OER) - because it quickly focused on how to integrate Creative Commons licences for teaching/learning material. See e.g. the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pressbooks.bccampus.ca/facultyoertoolkit/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Faculty OER Toolkit
}}}
 for further information on that topic.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Engaging non-academic actors}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Adoption of Open Scholarship at policy level by national and regional governments (like the way Open Data and Open Access have been widely adopted by governments).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Research is a highly competitive endeavour across the world. Due to the relative novelty of many Open Scholarship practices, it is understandable that institutes do not want to risk their reputation on a global playing field by adopting new operational processes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wider engagement of non-academic audiences, particularly members of the general public, is important to overcome any political inertia regarding Open Scholarship.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 7.2 Internal conditions \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Rate of growth}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab All current evidence indicates that Open Scholarship momentum is building, in terms of more widespread understanding of issues and adoption of practices (e.g., in terms of number of institutional Open Access policies, as indicated by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://roarmap.eprints.org/dataviz2.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ROARMAP
}}}
).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab But such diffusion is often slow and granular, and beset by frictions. Further experimentation should be encouraged to demonstrate the applicability of larger-scale adoption of practices and to increase the rate of growth, and ultimate impact, of Open Scholarship.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Avoiding quarrelling about details}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Often, the Open Scholarship movement seems to be fairly combatative about minute issues, without realizing amount of agreement on the main issues.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Focusing on the core principles and/or values and identifying that as a shared commonality sets fertile ground for further, productive discussion.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Overcoming lack of money}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Financial Sustainability is a key aspect for the future of Open Scholarship. A greater understanding of financial workflows in scholarly communication is required, and to support initiatives such as SCOSS, which is dedicated to supporting a sustainable and open scholarly infrastructure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Initiatives such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://intheopen.net/2017/09/join-the-movement-the-2-5-commitment/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
The 2.5% Commitment
}}}
 could be important in the future. This states simply that: "{\i Every academic library should commit to contribute 2.5% of its total budget to support the common infrastructure needed to create the open scholarly commons.}"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Thus, there is a clear scope for diverting funds away from present flows (e.g., subscriptions) into more sustainable Open Scholarship ventures. See also the consortium model mentioned above, of e.g. the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.openlibhums.org/site/about/the-olh-model/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Open Library of the Humanities
}}}
, which distributes the financial burden of individual libraries among a larger group of consortium members.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lack of patience among Open Scholarship proponents}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab We fully recognise the burdens and pressures that researchers already have, in maintaining high productivity levels, funding applications, administration, teaching, and other duties.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This means that often, Open Scholarship, is not highly prioritised, as the current reward system is still highly focused on publication of novel results in high impact journals, which can stifle the rate of growth.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Scholarship proponents need to be patient and understand this burden.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Seeing how diverse initiatives working at different speeds in different communities can still reinforce each other in working towards the same broad goals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Researchers do not necessarily need to be open activists. However, they should be aware of the functions of the wider scholarly communication system, and the diverse range of processes and norms that are involved in this.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Not being open to the limitations of openness}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Enthusiasm for openness carries the danger of not being receptive to critique or not acknowledging that there are situations where the standard open practices can have dangers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This may relate to privacy issues, but also to data that being open could be captured by governments for surveillance or by companies for corporate interests (think data on rare or indigenous plants/animals, or data showing how local groups or environmental groups work).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It also relates to being open to critique regarding the dangers of platform-based economies and unequal relation in research co-operations.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dealing with (lack of) diversity}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This includes an inherent bias towards English-speaking communities, which discriminates against those who do not speak this, either as their first language at all.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Open Scholarship must recognise that not all strategies are suitable for all regions, and allow for flexibility as such.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Related to this, the movement must make sure that other regions are not negatively impacted by decisions taken by other extrinsic groups.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 8. Opportunities \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Universities and research institutes from across the world are waking up to the promise of Open Scholarship. Discussions are happening at different levels, and universities in particular are in a strong position to help guide and develop policy frameworks, best practices, and education on the various aspects of Open Scholarship, including by providing administrative support.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Universities and research funders are in a position to adopt new practices in hiring, promotion, and tenure, and in particular control how Open Scholarship feeds in to this. Rewarding openness at this level is a key driver in the increased adoption of open practices.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Scholarly communication is a rapidly evolving landscape. There is a huge scope for systematic training and education in this domain, which could be adopted by research institutes. A huge global network of experts already exists with this professional capacity, but funding of such networks would be critical for any sort of sustainability. Platforms, communities and technologies already exist today that can support this movement.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Overall, there is a great opportunity now available to harmonise the scholarly communication policy landscape to simplify compliance for researchers. This would need to avoid license proliferation, with many one-off licences that may not be mutually compatible, and require too much work to interpret. Open source "solved" this with OSI-approved licenses, and MIT/BSD/GPL emerged as most common licenses with clearly understood mutual compatibility. The equivalent here for article and data licenses would be something equivalent to CC BY.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A combined approach of top-down policy changes and grassroots campaigning, advocacy, and training and education is needed to close the gap between positive attitudes to most aspects of Open Scholarship and the actual practices.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 9. Threats \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Barriers to Open Access adoption:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Some widely expressed examples here include:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of research into personal determinants and environmental conditions of (not) publishing Open Access;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lengthy, complex and confusing embargo periods to protect publisher revenues;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Time-consuming and expensive embargo compliance reconciliation systems;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Conflicts between funder and publisher policies;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Continued transferral of copyright from researchers to publishers;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of distributed article-processing charge funding;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Wide application of high and unsustainable APCs and BPCs, which are particularly discriminatory against specific demographics who might lack appropriate funds;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of knowledge in negotiating these difficulties;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of Awareness and acknowledgement of the fact that around {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://sustainingknowledgecommons.org/2018/02/06/doaj-apc-information-as-of-jan-31-2018/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
70% of journals indexed in the DOAJ
}}}
 do not charge article processing charges;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab No widely-agreed upon large-scale solution for issues regarding OA for books;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Continuing perceptions of lack of prestige for many OA journals; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A lack of appropriate offsetting deals around OA deals and hybrid journals.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A general lack of high profile role models for practices in all research disciplines, strengthening cultural inertia through a lack of awareness.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Barriers to data sharing:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of research into personal determinants and environmental conditions of (not) sharing data;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of skills and awareness of best practices;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of agreement on how Research Data Management (RDM) activities should be funded;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Licensing issues, and a lack of awareness surrounding them;\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lack of infrastructure to support good RDM throughout research lifecycle; and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Neglect to explicitly grant reuse rights in data, so they inherit poor reuse right from publications.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Incentives and metrics:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab A lack of suitable incentives creating fear from traditionally-embedded mentality and practices; for instance that sharing data reduces the competitiveness of an individual (e.g. "someone will use my data in the wrong way," or "I need to get 5 more publications out of this data"").\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Incentives must change to motivate and facilitate cultural change.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Continued reliance on non-transparent, non-reproducible metrics information from commercial providers will continue to be detrimental to scholarship.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab New metrics must be designed to create incentives to influence researcher behaviour, preferably based around openness.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Big commercial publishers}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Elsevier & Holtzbrinck/Springer Nature (via Digital Science) seem to be developing services for across the entire research workflow, from discovery through to funding. They have been referred to the European Commission antitrust authority for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://zenodo.org/record/1472045"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
anti-competitive practices
}}}
.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab These pose a definite threat in that they will start trying to bundle these services for institutions via "big deals" - so that institutions get locked into using non-transferable services for some things in order to have access to services they consider vital (i.e., same strategy used in bundling journals) ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170804/05454537924/elsevier-continues-to-build-monopoly-solution-all-aspects-scholarly-communication.shtml"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Moody 2017
}}}
; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://knowledgegap.org/index.php/sub-projects/rent-seeking-and-financialization-of-the-academic-publishing-industry/preliminary-findings/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Posada and Chen 2017
}}}
; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.sr.ithaka.org/blog/the-center-for-open-science-alternative-to-elsevier-announces-new-preprint-services-today/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Schonfeld 2017
}}}
)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This would ultimately lead to new inefficiencies, vendor lock-in, and the same price bloat we see associated with 'big deal' licensing contracts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Regarding preprints, there is an increasing colonisation of the landscape by commercial interests (e.g., Elsevier acquisition of SSRN and scientific publication workflow solutions company {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.elsevier.com/about/press-releases/corporate/elsevier-to-acquire-aries-systems-a-best-in-class-publication-workflow-solutions-provider"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Aries Systems
}}}
). This leads to wider commercial control, irrespective of the final venue of publication.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\b Resistance to change:}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Researchers are generally resistant to change, as is human nature, and often defined as a system of 'cultural inertia' within academia.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Giving them too much choice, as is common in Open Scholarship practices, could be off-putting, and lead to no change from traditional habits.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab People tend to choose things that are most similar to what they already have, or things that are most similar to other choices they have (e.g. see Dan Ariely's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.ted.com/talks/dan_ariely_asks_are_we_in_control_of_our_own_decisions"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
TED talk
}}}
 on making decisions).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 10. Outlook \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is important to make sure that people can still do what they are already doing, even if they participate in Open Scholarship. With {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.5334/bam"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Weller, 2014
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.19173/irrodl.v13i4.1313"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Veletsianos and Kimmons, 2016
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pbio.1002614"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
McKiernan, 2017
}}}
, among others, we see inclusivity as a crucial trait of the social movement that is Open Scholarship. While what we described here can ideally encompass all of the before-mentioned practices, an engagement in practices of open science and scholarship can be considered as happening in a spectrum of practices that each of us has to negotiate.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, future communication efforts must focus on open practices as not being completely new, but simply more efficient and more rewarding versions of current practices. Furthermore, it ought to be noted that Openness has a long and proud history and tradition in science and education - a tradition that might be worth reconsidering at our current situation at the beginning of the 21st century, so that the rhetorical question posed, among others, by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://doi.org/10.1186/s13059-015-0669-2"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Watson (2015)
}}}
 - "When will 'open science' become simply 'science'?" - can soon be answered with a "it has today!"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 11. Conclusions \par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 We are in the midst of a rapid, global evolution in tools, services and concepts in Open Scholarship; however, there has been little strategic co-ordination in the implementation of the various aspects of Open Scholarship. Simply channelling more time, effort, and funds into maintaining the existing system, with perverse incentives and skewed power dynamics, is clearly no longer sustainable for global research.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This document seeks to provide a comprehensive and strategic solution to this problem. By breaking down Open Scholarship into its constituent aspects, it encourages communities to take small steps as a collective towards a more open culture, and with relatively little effort. We provide substantial discussion into the pros and cons of these steps, rationale and potential threats, and existing strengths and enabling initiatives. We believe that co-ordinated implementation of this strategy will be necessary to ensure that we do not to fall back to solutions that would could stifle the further development of open research practices on a global level.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To avoid locking the research community into yet another business plan that only pays lip service to the guiding values, principles and practices of Open Scholarship, academia needs centre its scholarly practices on fundamental open principles, most importantly free access to, but also the possibility to freely participate in and re-use research output in all its forms. We see these freedoms as essential to any future of Open Scholarship.\par}
